<% content_for(:page_header) do %>
  <div>
    <h1>About XIVAuth Certificates</h1>
    <p>Certificates are an advanced feature. Most users will never need them.</p>
  </div>
<% end %>

<div class="alert alert-info">
  <details>
    <summary><strong>Document too long? Have a TL;DR!</strong></summary>
    <p class="pt-2 mb-0">
      Certificates allow you to use XIVAuth like a notary. You can use it to prove that something actually came from
      you, or to make sure that only you can read some information sent to you. Since certificates can be verified
      offline, they can unlock powerful use cases for building trust. However, it's important to keep in mind that
      certificates are not a silver bullet. They're primarily intended for high-assurance or decentralized systems and
      require careful implementation. Certificates are <strong>not</strong> a prerequisite for a system to be secure or
      trustworthy, and there are good reasons to not use them.
    </p>
  </details>
</div>

<h2>What is a certificate?</h2>

<p>
  A certificate is, fundamentally, a digital or mathematical proof of an identity. Certificates have two major uses:
  <em>signing</em> data (proving it came from you) and <em>encrypting</em> data (scrambling it so only the intended
  recipient can read it). In the former case, a certificate is the functional equivalent of a wax seal on an official
  document certifying it came from a specific entity. In the latter, the certificate is the equivalent of a lockbox and
  key; anyone may place anything into a lockbox, but only the owner can open it.
</p>

<p>
  When you create a certificate, your computer generates two mathematically linked keys: a private key and a public
  key. The private key is kept secret and is known only to you (or your computer), while the public key can be shared
  freely with anyone. Only the holder of the private key may sign (or "apply the seal") or decrypt ("open the lockbox")
  data through the certificate.
</p>

<p>
  XIVAuth acts as the authority that ties your public key to a verified character. When XIVAuth issues a certificate,
  it is essentially saying <em>"we're vouching that this stamp or lockbox belongs to this character."</em> So long as
  you trust XIVAuth to assert identities, and so long as you trust that your private key has not been stolen, you have
  implicit trust in that certificate.
</p>

<p>
  Certificates, however, have another special property: they can be verified fully offline and independently. This means
  that any data signed by a certificate can be independently verified by anyone without involving XIVAuth at all. This
  allows for trust relationships to be created quickly and efficiently and allows users to sign data without needing
  to reach back to XIVAuth.
</p>

<h2 class="pt-3">Why would I use a certificate?</h2>

Certificates have a few uses in the XIVAuth ecosystem. Ultimately, the system is flexible enough to allow developers to
create all sorts of interesting applications, but a few key examples are listed below:

<ul>
  <li class="my-3">
    <strong>Proving data came from your character.</strong><br>
    By signing some data with your certificate, other parties can trust that it came from you and not from a third
    party. This is particularly useful for proving ownership (or authenticity) of data: a digitally signed message in
    your name means that you are the one who wrote it.
  </li>
  <li class="my-3">
    <strong>Encrypting data for others.</strong><br>
    If you have a copy of a certificate for another player, you can encrypt data that only they can read. This allows
    the creation of secure channels for information without permitting eavesdropping by third parties. As an example,
    you can send a private message to another character and keep it truly private.
  </li>
  <li class="my-3">
    <strong>Authenticating to a service.</strong><br>
    Some services may choose to use a certificate for authentication purposes instead of a username and password.
    Since certificates tend to have reasonably long lives and private keys cannot be guessed, anyone holding a
    certificate can prove who they are.
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 class="pt-3">What's the downside?</h2>

<div class="alert alert-warning">
  Certificates are a very powerful and capable tool, but one that must be handled with care. The use of a certificate
  does not automatically imply that a system is secure, or that it's implemented properly. Likewise, the absence of
  certificate-based systems does not mean a system is insecure; there are many valid reasons for service owners to not
  want (or need) to implement certificates.
</div>

<p>
  While certificates are powerful, they do have practical limitations. Most critically, they rely on two key principles
  to remain true: the certificate issuer (in this case, XIVAuth) must be trustworthy, and the certificate holder (in 
  this case, the user) must retain sole control of their private key. If either of these conditions are violated, the 
  certificate should not be considered trustworthy. 
</p>

<p>
  Certificates are also not the right tool for every situation, and a service that does not use them is not less
  secure for it. Most services have a central point of trust already: the service itself. If you are willing to trust
  that the service will play fair, certificates add complexity without much practical benefit. The value shows up in
  decentralized or high-assurance systems where there is no single trusted server, or where you explicitly cannot rely
  on a middleman to handle things honestly. In those cases, certificates let you verify things end-to-end, independent
  of any service in between.
</p>

<hr>

<p class="text-muted">
